What is the Document Object Model (DOM)?
The Document Object Model (DOM) is a programming interface for web pages.
In simple words:
DOM is how JavaScript sees and controls your HTML page.
When a browser loads an HTML file, it doesn‚Äôt just display it. It converts the HTML into a structured model called the DOM.

The browser converts this:
                            <html>
                              <body>
                                <h1>Hello</h1>
                                <p>Welcome</p>
                              </body>
                            </html>

Into a tree structure like:
                            Document
                               ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ html
                                    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ body
                                         ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ h1
                                         ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ p
Each element becomes a node in the tree.

Why Is It Important?
Because JavaScript uses the DOM to:
Change text
Change styles
Add elements
Remove elements
Handle button clicks
Validate forms
Without DOM ‚Üí JavaScript cannot interact with HTML.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1Ô∏è‚É£ DOM Methods (How JS Finds & Changes HTML)
These are the tools JavaScript uses to talk to the DOM

üîπ getElementById()
document.getElementById("title")
Finds element by ID.

üîπ querySelector()
document.querySelector(".box")
Uses CSS selectors.
It returns first matching element.

üîπ querySelectorAll()
document.querySelectorAll(".box")

Returns NodeList (like array) of all matching elements.

‚úèÔ∏è Changing Content
element.innerText = "New Text"
element.innerHTML = "<b>Bold</b>"
üé® Changing Styles
element.style.color = "red"
element.style.backgroundColor = "black"
‚ûï Creating & Adding Elements
let newDiv = document.createElement("div")
newDiv.innerText = "Hello"

document.body.appendChild(newDiv)

Boom üí• New element appears on page.

2Ô∏è‚É£ DOM Events (How Pages React to Users)
Events make websites interactive.

Common Events
click
mouseover
keydown
submit
change

Example: Button Click
                          HTML:
                          <button id="btn">Click Me</button>

                          JavaScript:
                          let button = document.getElementById("btn")
                          button.addEventListener("click", function() {
                              alert("Button clicked!")
                          })

üëâ User clicks
üëâ Browser detects event
üëâ JS runs function

That‚Äôs interactivity.

‚ö° Event Flow (Advanced Concept)
There are 3 phases:
                              Capturing
                              Target
                              Bubbling
By default, JavaScript uses event bubbling (inner ‚Üí outer).
This becomes important in large apps.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
How DOM Works Internally in the Browser
Step 1: Browser Receives HTML
Server sends HTML file.

Step 2: HTML ‚Üí DOM Tree
Browser parser converts HTML into DOM tree.

Step 3: CSS ‚Üí CSSOM Tree
CSS is parsed into CSS Object Model.

Step 4: DOM + CSSOM ‚Üí Render Tree
Browser combines them.

Step 5: Layout & Paint
Browser calculates positions and displays pixels.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
How DOM Connects with JavaScript Engine
Now we enter real backend-level understanding.
JavaScript engine (like V8 in Chrome) does NOT directly know HTML.

It interacts with:
Browser APIs
The DOM is a Web API provided by the browser, not part of JavaScript itself.
